Dr. Jill Biden is traveling to Hanoi, Vietnam as part of her four-country visit to Asia. She is focusing on women's empowerment and educational opportunities for women and girls. Dr. Biden will participate in events in Japan as well, supporting service members, veterans, and military families through her Joining Forces initiative. She is accompanied by Catherine Russell, U.S. Ambassador-at-Large for Global Women's Issues, Scot Marciel, Principal Deputy Assistant Secretary of State, Bureau of East Asian and Pacific Affairs, and Christie Vilsack, Senior Advisor for International Education, USAID.

Upon arrival in Hanoi, Dr. Biden will commemorate the 20th anniversary of U.S.-Vietnam diplomatic relations by participating in an event highlighting the public-private partnership between the U.S. Embassy and the Asia Injury Prevention Foundation. The event, called Helmets for Kids, aims to provide bicycle helmets to Vietnamese children for their safety. She will also visit the Department of Defense POW/MIA Accounting Agency to learn about efforts to find missing military personnel from the Vietnam War. Dr. Biden will meet with members of Peace Trees, an American NGO that supports those affected by remnants of war.

Dr. Biden will meet with Vietnamese Vice President Nguyen Thi Doan to discuss women's issues and Vietnam's higher education system. In the evening, she will deliver remarks at a reception for Vietnamese women leaders hosted by the U.S. Ambassador to Vietnam.

The next day, Dr. Biden will visit the Temple of Literature in Hanoi to meet with Mai Thi Hanh, wife of President Sang of Vietnam. They will discuss the progress made since establishing diplomatic relations and potential areas for expanded cooperation, particularly in women and education. She will also visit the Ba Vi Orphanage to learn about U.S. government efforts to combat HIV and AIDS. Later, she will depart Hanoi for Ho Chi Minh City.